Project Pitch: 00118188
Topic Area: SBIR/STTR: Learning and Cognition Technologies (LC)
Invite Date: 7/13/2026

Dear Lu,

Upon reviewing your submitted Project Pitch, I am pleased to invite you to =
submit a full Phase I proposal to the U.S. National Science Foundation=92s =
(NSF) Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR)/Small Business Technology T=
ransfer (STTR) program. Your full proposal (based on the project proposed i=
n the associated Project Pitch) must be submitted within the submission per=
iod that is active on the date of your invitation or within the subsequent =
submission period that is offered; for example, if a Project Pitch invite i=
s received on June 30, 2024, you may submit your full proposal for either o=
f the next two deadlines (September 18, 2024 or November 6, 2024). This inv=
itation can only be used once for a single full proposal submission (i.e. c=
annot be used for multiple full proposal submissions).


Please submit your proposal to the Learning and Cognition Technologies (LC)=
 topic as soon as you are ready. Some points to consider as you develop you=
r proposal include;

Dear Lu,

Please submit your proposal to the Learning and Cognition Technologies topi=
c when you are ready. Be sure to include sufficient technical details in th=
e experimental plan along with specific milestones and quantitative success=
 metrics and details of how you will achieve the desired outcomes. Our prop=
osals are not pitches for ideas, they are thorough plans that you will exec=
ute so the 7-10 page R&D plan should spend most of the pages on how/what ex=
periments/what might not work and why and what might be an alternative appr=
oach, etc. Follow the guidelines in the Project Description portion of our =
revised and most recent solicitation (see here: https://seedfund.nsf.gov/so=
licitation-proposal/) and this document: https://hw898.ise.msstate.edu/file=
s/research_101_for_engineers.pdf. Some points to consider as you develop th=
e content for your proposal include:

Technical:
1. What are the key technology risks/problems specific to your approach (no=
t the market or industry problems, but problems with your technology that a=
re preventing it from achieving the desired results?
2. What is the proposed innovation to solving the problems? If there has be=
en work done on the innovation, what are the new scientific/engineering ele=
ments to be developed that will address the technical risks? What are plans=
 should certain aspects of the approach not work?
3. Provide an experimental plan that clearly describes the research objecti=
ves and a discussion of how you intend on achieving the objectives. What se=
t of quantitative metrics will you use to assess the outcome of the innovat=
ion research described in the plan? What are the range of values [or specif=
ic values] for target specifications that will establish proof of concept i=
n Phase I? Why are these target metrics appropriate, and how do they eviden=
ce success.
4. What skills, capabilities and resources will be included in the work to =
successfully demonstrate feasibility?
5. What intellectual property does the company currently have? Future IP de=
velopment? What license terms (if any) exist?

Broader Impacts:
1. What is the motivation for the company to take on this project?
2. Clearly articulate how the proposed technology will result in a societal=
 benefit. Which communities will benefit and on what timeline?
3. How will the societal benefits be measured and tracked?
4. What steps are being taken to recognize and minimize the unintended cons=
equences of the proposed technology?

Commercial:
1. What is the background of the team, why is this the right team to execut=
e the commercialization of the proposed innovation?
2. What is the size and scope of the market opportunity? You must identify =
how you plan to make a scalable, sustainable business from this effort.
3. Who is the customer for the innovation? What is the value proposition fo=
r your customer?
4. What does the competitive landscape look like? What is your competitive =
advantage? (Please search NSF awards database for prior similar technology =
awards)
5. Which group of customers want the product/technology being proposed?
6. What customer(s) needs or requirements will be satisfied by the proposed=
 product? Is this a need to have or a nice to have?
7. How are the needs and requirement(s) being satisfied now?
8. Why will the customer choose the proposed product over existing solution=
s?

Be sure to provide supporting evidence for any claims made in the proposal.


To prepare your full Phase I proposal, please follow the NSF SBIR/STTR guid=
elines and instructions as outlined in the Phase I solicitation. You may us=
e this invitation to submit either an SBIR or an STTR proposal, but not bot=
h.


NSF SBIR/STTR Phase I Solicitation

SBIR - No partnership requirement; partnerships are allowed. The small busi=
ness must perform a minimum of two-thirds of the research, as measured by t=
he budget.

STTR - Requires a partnership with an eligible research institution. A smal=
l business must perform a minimum of 40% of the research, as measured by th=
e budget, and a minimum of 30% must be performed by the partner research in=
stitution.

To receive an award, you must meet the eligibility criteria as a small busi=
ness (see section IV of the solicitation document and the SBIR/STTR Eligibi=
lity Guide for details). Proposals that do not comply with the guidelines o=
r do not meet the listed eligibility requirements outlined in the solicitat=
ion may be returned without review.

Please save this email. This email invitation must be uploaded as part of y=
our Phase I proposal submission in the =93Additional Single Copy Documents=
=94 section of the Research.gov System.

Please also make sure to select the following topic area from the drop-down=
 menu when completing the NSF SBIR Phase I Cover Page for your proposal: Le=
arning and Cognition Technologies (LC). For a list of sub-topic areas, plea=
se review our most recent solicitation topic and subtopic.



I recommend starting the required governmental and NSF registrations immedi=
ately (See more information about the registrations on the full proposal pa=
ge). The System for Award Management (SAM) registration process is free but=
 can take up to a month to complete. You MUST have an active SAM.gov regist=
ration number to register with NSF and submit an invited full proposal thro=
ugh Research.gov. Sam.gov registration must be renewed annually.



Please refer to the NSF=92s website for more information about proposal pre=
paration and we invite you to join us at an upcoming webinar Office Hours: =
SBIR/STTR Proposal Prep via Zoom: Events

We look forward to receiving your Phase I proposal. Please let me know if y=
ou have questions.


Thank you,
Lindsay Portnoy

America=92s Seed Fund powered by NSF
National Science Foundation
Alexandria, VA 22314
lportnoy@salesforce.nsf.gov

